amaze
==English==
===Etymology===
From {{inh|en|enm|*amasen||to bewilder, perplex}}, from {{inh|en|ang|āmasian||to confuse, astonish}}, from {{m|ang|ā-|pos=perfective prefix}} + {{m|ang|*masian||to confound}}, equivalent to {{prefix|en|a|maze}}.
===Pronunciation===
* {{a|UK}} {{IPA|en|/əˈmeɪz/}}
* {{audio|en|En-us-amaze.ogg|Audio (US)}}
* {{rhymes|en|eɪz|s=2}}
===Verb===
{{en-verb}}
# {{lb|en|transitive}} To fill with wonder and surprise; to [[astonish]], [[astound]], [[surprise]] or [[perplex]]. {{defdate|from 16th c.}}
#: {{ux|en|He was '''amazed''' when he found that the girl was a robot.}}
#* {{RQ:KJV|Matthew|12|23|passage=And all the people were '''amazed''', and said, Is not this the son of David?}}
#* '''1759''', {{w|Oliver Goldsmith}}, ''The Present State of Polite Learning''
#*: Spain has long fallen from '''amazing''' Europe with her wit, to amusing them with the greatness of her Catholic credulity.
# {{lb|en|intransitive}} To undergo amazement; to be astounded.
#*{{quote-book|en|1890|{{w|Bayard Taylor}}|Faust: A Tragedy|passage=Eye is blinded, ear '''amazes'''.}}
# {{lb|en|obsolete}} To [[stupefy]]; to knock unconscious. {{defdate|13th|17th c.}}
# {{lb|en|obsolete}} To bewilder; to stupefy; to bring into a maze.
#* {{RQ:Shakespeare Venus and Adonis|passage=a labyrinth to '''amaze''' his foes}}
# {{lb|en|obsolete}} To [[terrify]], to fill with [[panic]]. {{defdate|16th|18th c.}}
#* {{RQ:Burton Melancholy}}, New York Review Books 2001, p.261:
#*: [Fear] '''amazeth''' many men that are to speak or show themselves in public assemblies, or before some great personages {{...}}
